Importance of Running Back vs Offensive Line for Run Game

James Boggs

American Football, specifically the National Football League (NFL) is the most watched sport in the united states. If you aren't familiar with how the game is played you can read about the rules here. In this tutorial we are going to be looking at two positions in particular, running backs and offensive linemen. If you are unfamiliar with the positions you can read about them here. Running Backs are a position that gets a lot of spotlight in the NFL, the top performing ones will be known by most fans of the game. However, in order for a running back to be successful, they rely on a lot of other player, primarily, the offensive line needs to do a good job of blocking to create holes in the defense for the running back to run through. The goal of this tutorial is to investigate how much of a productive run game is due to a good running back vs good offensive linemen, and further to look into how to predict how good of a run game a team will have based on the players they have in these positions.

Where is the Data Doming From¶

To do the analysis in this tutorial we are going to look at data on the game stats of individual players as well as teams and also look at player salary data. Player statistics are gotten from the website Football Outsider A database for player statistics. This website does require an account to access it's data but making an account is completely free and only requires email verification. Team statistics will be gotten from the website espn.com. Lastly, Data on player pay will be collected from the website Spotrac. In order to access the more that the past three years of data on spotrac requires a paid account, if you don't want to pay for an account then just do analysis on the past 3 years only.

Scraping the Data¶

The code is written in python 3 and makes use of these imported libraries: pandas, requests, BeautifulSoup, matplotlib, numpy, re, statsmodel, and scikit-learn. The puropose of each of these will be explained as they get used.

In [3]:
# turn multi index column labels with 2 values into a sigle index
# input is the dataframe to be changed, and wether or not to include the first value in the multi index in the new label
def remove_muli_index(table, merge=False):
    # fill up an array with all the new column labels
    new_columns = []
    for c in table.columns:
        if merge:
            new_columns.append(c[0] + " " + c[1])
        else:
            new_columns.append(c[1])
            
    # assign the new column labels to the given dataframe
    table.columns = new_columns

Player Stats¶

First we will scrape data on stats for running backs and offensive lines from the site Football Outsider. To do this we will use the requests library to make http requests from our code. Then we will use the BeautifulSoup library to extract the data we want from the html that was returned by the websites. The Football Outsider site requires we log in to access its data so first create an account then we will have to login to this account using the request module before requesting the data. In order to log in we need to see what data the site expects to receive with a post request for logging in. This is all shown down below but if you are curious how this is found from a site then here is how. Go to the website and inspect it, then fill out the username and password and login in, after that you can go to the network tab then click on payload in order to see what data was sent to the website.

Now that the session is logged in we can get the data from the site. The data is requested from the session then processed by BeautifulSoup which lets us search for particular html tags. In this case we want to pull out all the tables because these are what is holding all the data. First we will get data on the offensive line. This is all stores in one table on the site so all we have to do is store the table in a pandas dataframe then rename some columns, remove a cumulative NFL entry in the table and add the year. Then just add together the dataframes from each year. The final result will be a table where each row is the stats on the offensive line for one team on a particular year.

In [5]:
# create empty dataframe to accumulate data from each year
line_stats_table = pd.DataFrame()

# get the table for each year from the site
for year in years:
    # request the html from the site
    r = session1.get("https://www.footballoutsiders.com/stats/nfl/basic-offensive-line/" + str(year))

    # read the html and find the desired table with Beautiful soup
    root1 = BeautifulSoup( r.content )
    t = root1.find("table")
    
    # save the table into a pandas dataframe
    temp = pd.read_html(t.prettify())[0]

    # remove an empty column that gets created
    temp.drop([("PASS PROTECTION", "Unnamed: 15_level_1")], axis=1, inplace=True)
    
    # remove the final enty in the table which is a cumulative one for the whole NFL and doesn't represent an individual team
    temp.drop([32], axis=0, inplace = True)
    
    # rename the columns to be single index
    remove_muli_index(temp)
    
    # add a year column to the table
    temp["year"] = year
    
    # add the table for one year to the accumulated table
    line_stats_table = line_stats_table.append(temp)
    
# reset the index
line_stats_table = line_stats_table.reset_index().drop(["index"],axis=1)

# change the abbreviation for jacksonville so it matches whats in the teams table
line_stats_table.replace(['JAX'],'JAC', inplace=True)

    # add the table for one year to the accumulated table

The process for getting the pay for offensive linemen and running backs is exactly the same so we can create on function to use for both. The data is gathered on by year and by team, when choosing the team some work needs to be done to ensure the right url is used for teams that have changed their name or location during the period we are looking at. Once the table is read we clean up some columns we don't want, rename some for convenience, and split up player name and team which are stored together in one column on the site. We also change the form of the player names to be first letter of first name then last name so it matches with the player stat data we collected earlier. We then Store the data in two dataframes, one for individual players and one that is the sum of the amount spent total by a team on that position. The final result is four tables, a table where each row is an individual player for a particular year and a table where each row is one team for a particular year, one of each of these tables for running backs and offensive linemen.

In [12]:
# get pay data for a given position and return a team table and an individual table
def scrape_pay_data(position):
    
    # create empty dataframe to accumulate data from each year
    individual_table = pd.DataFrame()
    team_table = pd.DataFrame()
    
    # go through each year and each team and get the table for them
    for year in years:
        for i in range(teams.shape[0]):
            # ensure that the team name is the correct one for that year
            
            # set name and city to the current one
            city = teams["city"].iat[i]
            name = teams["name"].iat[i]
            # check if team has an old name that they used during this year
            if (not teams["switch year"].isnull().iat[i]) and year < teams["switch year"].iat[i]:
                # set name city to the old ones
                city = teams["old city"].iat[i]
                name = teams["old name"].iat[i]
                
            # request the html from the site
            r = session2.get('https://www.spotrac.com/nfl/rankings/' + str(year) + 
                             '/contract-average-cap-pct/' + city + '-' + name + '/' + position + '/')

            # read the html and find the desired table with Beautiful soup
            root1 = BeautifulSoup( r.content )
            t = root1.find("table")
            
            # save the table into a pandas dataframe
            temp = pd.read_html(t.prettify())[0]
    
            # delete some columns that aren't needed
            temp.drop(["Unnamed: 0"], axis=1, inplace=True)
            temp.drop(["Signed Year"], axis=1, inplace=True)
            
            # rename a columns for convenience
            temp.rename(columns={"contract average cap pct":"cap %"}, inplace=True)
    
    
            # split up the columns that contains player name and team into two columns
        
            # create a column of the player name and team in a list split up by whitespace
            temp["name and team"] = temp["Player"].str.split()
            temp["team"] = ""
    
            # go through each row
            for j in range(temp.shape[0]):
                # set the team column to the last item in the name and team list which is the team
                temp.at[j, "team"] = temp.at[j, "name and team"][-1]
                
                # set the player column to the First letter of the first name plus the last name
                temp.at[j, "Player"] = temp.at[j,"name and team"][0][0] + ". " + temp.at[j,"name and team"][1]
            temp.drop(["name and team"], axis=1, inplace=True)
    
            # add a year column to the table
            temp["year"] = year
            # convert the cap % column to type float
            temp["cap %"] = temp["cap %"].replace('[\%,]', '', regex=True).astype(float)
            
            # add the table for one year to the accumulated individual table
            individual_table = individual_table.append(temp.copy())
            
            # temporarily remove year column so it doesn't get summed
            temp.drop(["year"], axis=1, inplace=True)
            
            # add a column for number of players
            temp["number"] = 1
            
            # sum the player pay for the current team
            temp = temp.groupby(['team']).sum()
            
            # add back the year column
            temp["year"] = year
            
            # add the table for one year to the accumulated team table
            team_table = team_table.append(temp.reset_index())
            
    # reset the index
    individual_table = individual_table.reset_index().drop(["index"],axis=1)
    
    return individual_table, team_table
    
# call the function for offensive linemen and running backs
line_pay_table, team_line_pay_table = scrape_pay_data("offensive-line")
rb_pay_table, team_rb_pay_table = scrape_pay_data("running-back")

Team Stats¶

Finally, we collect data on team stats from espn.com. This site does not need to be logged in to in order to access the data so the process is a bit simpler to get the html. We just need to get the table for each year from the website and rename some columns. However, the data on the website gets divided into two tables during this process so they need to be put back together. After that we need to work with the team name column so that it can be matched up with the teams in the teams table.

In [15]:
# create empty dataframe to accumulate data from each year
team_stats_table = pd.DataFrame()

for year in years:
    # request the html from the site
    r = requests.get('https://www.espn.com/nfl/stats/team/_/season/' + str(year) + '/seasontype/2')

    # read the html and find the desired tables with Beautiful soup
    root1 = BeautifulSoup( r.content )
    tables = root1.find_all("table")
    
    # save the first table into a pandas dataframe, moving the first entry from the column label back into the data
    temp = pd.read_html(tables[0].prettify())[0].T.reset_index().T.reset_index(drop=True)
    
    # rename the column
    temp.columns = ['team']
    
    # save the second table into a pandas dataframe
    temp2 = pd.read_html(tables[1].prettify())[0]
    
    # rename the columns to be single index
    remove_muli_index(temp2, merge=True)
    
    # join the two columns back together
    temp = temp.join(temp2, how='outer')
    
    # rename the games played column
    temp.rename(columns={'Unnamed: 0_level_0 GP': 'GP'}, inplace=True)
    
    # add a year column to the table
    temp["year"] = year
    team_stats_table = team_stats_table.append(temp)
    
# reset the index
team_stats_table.reset_index(inplace=True)
team_stats_table.drop(["index"], axis=1, inplace=True)

# change the name of washington so it is consistent
team_stats_table['team'] = team_stats_table['team'].replace(['Washington', 'Washington Redskins'],'Washington football-team')

# convert the city and team name into jsut the team name
team_stats_table["city and name"] = team_stats_table['team'].str.split()
team_stats_table["team"] = ""
for i in range(team_stats_table.shape[0]):
    team_stats_table.at[i, "team"] = team_stats_table.at[i, "city and name"][-1].lower()
team_stats_table.drop(["city and name"], axis=1, inplace=True)

# add in the team abbreviation by joining it with part of the teams table
team_stats_table = team_stats_table.set_index('team').join(teams[["abbreviation", "name"]].set_index('name'),how="inner")
team_stats_table = team_stats_table.reset_index().drop(["index"], axis=1).rename(columns={"abbreviation":"team"})

Data Visualization and Analysis¶

Now that all the data is collected we can begin analyzing it. In order to determine the impact of the running back vs offensive line on the running game of a team, we need a way to evaluate the quality of the linemen and the running back as well as how well a teams run game is. Evaluating the quality of these two positions is the biggest problem. The reason why we are investigating this question in the place is that it's hard to evaluate ones performance independent of the other. The way we will attempt to do this first is by looking at how much players are paid. Coaches and scouts spend lots of time looking at game film to evaluate individual players performances and will pay the ones who they think are the best more. So looking at player pay gives us a way to measure something that's at least correlated with how good an individual player is. For evaluating how good a teams run game we will first use the number of rushing yards they produced during a season. With these to measures we can make a basis first visualization which we can later go on to refine.

Preparing the Data¶

in order to make the proposed plot we need to combine data from the team pay tables as well as the team stat tables.

Note on Player Pay¶

In the NFL teams have a salary cap, which is the maximum amount the team can spend on all of their players. This salary cap increases fairly quickly over time which means players tend to get paid more as time passes. To account for this and evenly compare teams from different years, we are using percent of cap space as the measures of a players salary so that their salary is normalized with respect to the salary cap.

Graphing Total Rushing Yards Vs. % of Cap Space Spent on Running Backs/Offensive Line¶

We can now create a scatterplot for each position of these two measurements along with a line of best fit which we can make using the close form linear algebra solution and the math library numpy to help visualize and measure what their relationship is.

In [17]:
# graphs the given two columns of the given table with the given title as a scatterplot with line of best fit
# return the prepared X and Y matrix for analysis
def graph_with_line(table, xcol, ycol, xtitle, ytitle):
    
    # set up the aesthetics, title, and labels for the graph
    fig= pyplot.figure(figsize=(12,6))
    pyplot.xticks(fontsize=14)
    pyplot.xlabel(xtitle, fontsize=20)
    pyplot.yticks(fontsize=14)
    pyplot.ylabel(ytitle, fontsize=20)
    pyplot.title(xtitle + " Vs. " + ytitle, fontsize=24)
    
    # x variable vs the y variable
    pyplot.plot(table[xcol], table[ycol], 'o') 
    
    # create a line of best fit

    # set up the x and y from the data
    X = np.zeros((table.shape[0],2))
    Y = np.zeros(table.shape[0])
    for i in range(table.shape[0]):
        X[i][0] = 1
        X[i][1] = table[xcol].iat[i]
        Y[i] = table[ycol].iat[i]

    # solve using the close form equation
    params = np.linalg.solve(X.T.dot(X), X.T.dot(Y))

    # plot the line of best fit
    pyplot.plot(pyplot.xticks()[0],pyplot.xticks()[0] * params[1] + params[0], label='Line of Best Fit')
    pyplot.legend(loc="upper left")
    
    return X, Y

The First thing you may notice just by looking at the graph or at the low R squared value in the stat test is that the variables are not highly correlated with each other. This is not surprising though. There are lots of other factors that go into how many rushing yards a team gets in a year such as the number of run plays the team runs, how good the play calls are, what quality of opponents the team faces among many more. Among all these factors we wouldn't expect just one measure to determine too much about how many rushing yards the team gets. Looking further into the R squared value we can see that it is higher for the running back pay variable, this would seem to suggest that the running back's skill has more impact on the run game of a team than the skill of the offensive line. However this result is not very conclusive yet, Looking at the P values for our two variables, the running back pay seems pretty significant, while the offensive line pay is a lot less statistically meaningful. In order to get a more sure result we will try to refine our model by trying to account for some more factors.

Refining the Variables¶

First looking at total rushing yards there are a couple ways that come to mind to improve this measure for how good the run game for a team is. One is that this measure includes rushing yards by the quarterback. We are only interested in the yards that running backs produce so we want to make sure those yards are not included. Furthermore the amount of rushing yards is dependent on how many runs a team attempts, to control for this we can instead look at the number of yards per attempt that a running back gets. In order to look at just the yards from running backs we can look at individual running backs yards instead of the whole team, this also gives us data on the number of runs since that is included in our individual stat table.

Preparing the Data¶

In order to make this new graph we need to combine data from the individual running back stat, individual running back pay, and team offensive line pay table. First we need to match up running backs from the pay table and the stat table. Next we need to assign each of them a team offensive line pay value for their team.

This time the results seems very much the opposite of last time, this time the offensive line seems to have much more effect on the run game. One possible explanation is that teams who are planning on running more often are more willing to spend more on running backs, that would explain why total rushing yards is correlated with running back pay while average yards per attempt does not seem to be correlated. This is only one possibility among many though. Looking at the p value for the lineman pay it seems to be significantly correlated with average yards per attempt, it still has a low R squared value though. This means that there are still a lot of other factors that go into the average yards per attempt. One thing that can still be messing up our average yards per attempt is outliers, must runs are short with few going over 10 yards. However every once in a while the running back gets away from the defense and can get a run 50 yards or more. These long runs can skew the average higher than it should be. Unfortunately there is no data on individual runs in the data we got so we can not try looking at the median.

If these statistics work like intended then we would expect them to be more correlated to pay than average yards per attempt. To see if this is true we can graph them.

The correlation between running back pay and DYAR is much stronger than with average yards per attempt. That means this statistic is likely doing a good job for what it was intended to do. The correlation between offensive line pay and adjusted line yards is very similar to with average yards per attempt. That means that this stat isn't really doing a good job of capturing the performance on the offensive line independent of the running back.

Concluding Importance of Running Backs Vs. Offensive Line¶

One thing that is clear is that there a lot of factors that go into how well a teams run game will be on a given year. Exactly how much is due to the skill of running backs or the offensive line is hard to tell, both because it is hard to measure their individual skill in the first place and also because there is a lot that goes into how well the run game is. The results we've seen seem to indicate that the skill of the offensive line has more impact but it is far from conclusive. For evaluating them individually with stats, the DYAR stat from Football Outsider seems to do a good job for running backs, while evaluating the offensive lines still needs some better solutions.

Predictive Model¶

Fantasy Football¶

Fantasy football is a game that people play where you have to choose players from the NFL you think will perform well to put on your team, if you aren't familiar with the game you can read more here). In fantasy football one of the positions that is included is running backs. Running backs score points based on how many rushing yards they get. So being able to predict that before a season will lead to choosing better running backs. Looking at stats from previous years can give a good idea to potential performance. But in scenarios where a good running back is switching teams and you want to know if they will still do good with a new offensive line you can't rely too much on just looking at how many yards they had the previous year. To create an aid to help in that situation we will create a Nearest Neighbor Regressor in order to predict the performance of a running back paired with a particular offensive line.

k-NN Regressor¶

We will use the k-NN regressor implemented in the machine learning library scikit-learn to make our model. As input we will use the pay for a running back and their offensive line and also the DYAR. Since DYAR is based on the stats from a season we need to use the DYAR from the previous seasons or else we wouldn't be able to predict anything. We will try to predict the number of yards the running back will have over the season. First we need to prepare out training data.

Training Data¶

We need to get the appropriate data from our running back table then split it into training data for the model, validation data so we can tune hyperparameters and holdout data so we can evaluate its performance at the end. We will use 80% training data, 10% validation data, and 20% holdout data.

In [36]:
# create a table with DYAR values from the year before
temp = rb_table[["DYAR", "year", "team", "Player"]]
temp["year"] = temp["year"] + 1
temp.rename(columns={"DYAR": "DYAR last"}, inplace=True)

# get the data and labels from the running back table
examples = pd.merge(rb_table, temp, how='inner', on=['year', 'team', 'Player'])[["cap %", "line cap %", "DYAR last", "Yards"]]
data = examples[["cap %", "line cap %", "DYAR last"]]
labels = examples[["Yards"]]

# split up the data into training data and holdout data
training_data, holdout_data, training_labels, holdout_labels = train_test_split(data, labels, test_size = 0.20)

# further split the training data up into training data and validation data
training_data, validation_data, training_labels, validation_labels = train_test_split(training_data, training_labels, test_size = 0.125)

Hyperparameters¶

The two hyperparameters we will try to tune are the number of neighbors included in the model and whether or not the value oof distant neighbors are weighted lower, we will try from 1 to 299 neighbors and both options of weights for each of these. The resulting model will then be tested on the validation set each time to see which combination performs the best. We will evaluate how well one performs using mean squared error.

In [37]:
# number of different amounts of neighbors to try
n = 299

# keep track of the best model and its hyperparameters
best_kNN = None
min_error = -1
n_neighbors = 0
weights = ''
error_list = []

# generate a model for each combination of hyperparameters
for w in ['uniform', 'distance']:
    for i in range(1,n+1):
    
        # load a kNN Regressor from scikit-learn
        kNN = KNeighborsRegressor(n_neighbors=i, weights=w)
        
        # train the model using our training data and training labels
        kNN.fit(training_data, training_labels)
        
        # predict the validation data with the model
        predicted_labels = kNN.predict(validation_data)
        
        # check the error of the model
        error = metrics.mean_squared_error(validation_labels, predicted_labels)
        error_list.append(error)
        
        # save the model if it has performed the best so far
        if min_error == -1:
            min_error = error
        if error < min_error:
            min_error = error
            n_neighbors = i
            weights = w
            best_kNN = kNN

Now we can look at the error of the models as the number of neighbors increased

pass

As the number oh neighbors went up both weight functions quickly decreased until they hit a minimum then gradually started to increase again. This is a common thing to see in machine learning as you increase model complexity. Another interesting thing to not is that the uniform weight function increased much faster than the distance weighted function. This makes sense since the more neighbors that are checked the farther away they get so the distance weighted function puts a very low weight on them and they don't affect the result as much.

While this model was not very accurate using the data we had it can still be one thing to be taken into consideration when selecting a running back for fantasy football.

Conclusion¶

Predicting football statistics is complicated. This is easy to see by the fact that many experts have wildly different opinions about what will happen before each season. In order to further strengthen the predictive model we created it would be interesting to see what additional data could be used to help. It will certainly never very accurate but the better it can be the more useful it could become. In looking into the impact of running backs and offensive lines on the run game we needed to scrape data from a variety of sources then use techniques to clean and combine this data so that we could use it together. We then created visualizations and used statistical tests to draw conclusions from the data. We also used machine learning to create a predictive model using the statistics we had identified in the previous analysis.

If you are interested in football stats then there is plenty more to look at, we only investigating runs in this tutorial which is only one small part of the game, There are plenty of other positions and stats to look at and draw conclusions from.
